<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-456-598  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 456 598.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  July 25 1989 v3 n27 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Photolink beams data down to Mac: Infrared light links Macswithout cables. (Photonics Corp infrared network connection)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Garner, Rochelle.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Photonics Corp. (product development)Apple Computer Inc. (investment activities).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Photonics Photolink (Computer communications equipment) (productdevelopment).andO;Topic:     Local Area NetworksCablesInfrared TechnologyConnectivityAdd-In-On DevicesOffice Equipment.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Infrared light links Macs without cablesandM;By Rochelle GarnerandM;Campbell, Calif.andP;  -- Network managers who are tired of wiring headaches cansoon turn to Photo-link, a system that beams data among computers by bouncingpulses of invisible infrared  light off the ceiling.andM;Backed by funding from Apple, among others, the developer, Photonics Corp.,andO;plans to release in September one version of its hardware for AppleTalk LANsand another for RS-232 terminal-to-host connections.andP;  Token-ring and 3270implementations are due next year, with an Ethernet link expected in 1991.andO;Photolink runs at the full speed of whatever type of network to which it isconnected.andM;Mounted on an office partition, each $995 Photolink unit can be hooked up toas many as four computers.andP;  The units are then linked by aiming the infraredlight each generates at a common spot on the ceiling.andP;  The system works onlywithin a single open or partitioned office, but can be mixed with cablingconnecting to other rooms or larger networks.andM;&quot;On average, companies move once every three years; companies that use lotsof computers move every two years.andP;  Every time they move, they have anotherwiring decision to make,&quot; said Dick Allen, president of Photonics.andP;  &quot;As I goaround, no one asks why you would want to eliminate cabling -- everyone knowswhat a mess it is.&quot;andM;Allen said that he sees Photonics' customers as large organizations inindustry and government because &quot;two-thirds of U.S.andP;  office workers areemployed in open office environments, and the percentage is higher for largerorganizations.&quot;andM;Photonics Corp. is located at 200 E. Hacienda Ave., Campbell, Calif.andP;  95008;(408) 370-3033.andP;  n</TEXT></DOC>